Linux is an operating system that has many differrent types-----linux distribution like Ubuntu,Debian e.t.c 
Linux is powerful via terminal. Here's a guide to essential commands and features for efficient management.

Basic Commands:
ls: List directory contents (ls -l | more for long lists).
pwd: Print working directory.
mv: Move/rename files (mv source dest).
cp: Copy files (cp source dest).
rm: Remove files/directories (rm -r for dirs).
chown: Change file owner/group (sudo chown owner:group file).
su/sudo: Elevate privileges (sudo for single command, su for session).

Permissions & Packages:
chmod: Change file modes (chmod 744 file; r=4, w=2, x=1).
apt-get: Manage packages (sudo apt-get install app).
yum: RPM package manager (yum install app).

Network & System:
ip: Manage interfaces (ip address, ip route).
df: Disk free space (df -h for human-readable).
grep: Search text in files (grep pattern file).
ps: View processes (ps -e for all).
top: Monitor CPU/RAM usage.
find: Locate files (find . -name "*.txt").
dig: DNS lookup.

Editors & Tools:
cat: Concatenate/display files (cat file1 file2 > output).
nano: Simple text editor.

Linux Features:
Backups: tar (archive), rsync (sync files).
Updates: apt-get/yum, graphical updaters, software center.
Anti-Virus: ClamAV; keep signatures updated.
Shell/Terminal: Command-line access for scripts/config.
Samba: SMB for Windows file/print sharing and AD integration.

